synchronized vs volatile
Synchronized:
  Provides mutual exclusion (lock)
  Only one thread at a time can access
  Ensures atomicity + visibility
Volatile:
  no atomicity only visibility
  no lock
  faster
  Guarantees:Changes made by one thread are visible to others immediately
  Why is count++ not thread-safe even with volatile?  
    Because it is not atomic. Read, write and increement. 
    fix using synchronization or AtomicInteger.incrementAndGet()

1. The Problem: CPU Caching
  Modern processors are so fast that they don't always read from main RAM. Instead, each CPU core has its own local cache (L1/L2).
  Thread A reads a variable and stores it in its local cache.
  Thread A updates the variable.
  Thread B reads the variable, but it reads the "stale" (old) value from the main RAM or its own cache because Thread A
        hasn't flushed its update back to the main memory yet.
  This is known as the Visibility Problem.

2. The Solution: volatile
  When you mark a variable as volatile, you are telling the JVM:
    No Caching: Always read and write directly to the Main Memory (RAM).
    Happens-Before Relationship: It creates a guarantee that any write to a volatile field happens before subsequent reads of that same field.

    public class SharedFlag {
        private volatile boolean active = true;
    
        public void stop() {
            active = false; // Immediately visible to all threads
        }
    
        public void run() {
            while (active) {
                // Do work
            }
        }
    }
3. What volatile is NOT (Important!)
    A common mistake is thinking volatile replaces synchronized. It does not.
    No Atomicity: volatile does not guarantee that compound operations are safe.
        If you have volatile int counter = 0; and two threads call counter++, you can still lose data. 
        This is because counter++ is actually three steps: (1) Read, (2) Increment, (3) Write. 
        volatile only helps with the "Read/Write" part, not the logic in between.
    
    No Locking: It doesn't block other threads from accessing the variable.

When to use it in Microservices
  In a backend environment (like your AKS pods), you typically use volatile for:
      Status Flags: A flag that tells a background worker thread to shut down.
      Double-Checked Locking: Used inside a Singleton pattern to ensure the instance is correctly published across threads.
      Lightweight Heartbeats: Checking if a service connection is still "alive" without the overhead of heavy synchronization.
  If you need to perform math (like a counter) across threads, don't use volatile. Instead, use Atomic Classes like AtomicInteger or AtomicLong.

