What is a Future?
    Introduced in Java 5, a Future acts as a placeholder for a result that will eventually appear.

The Problem with Future
    The main issue with a standard Future is that it is blocking and passive. 
    To get the result, you must call .get(), which stops the current thread until the task completes. 
    You cannot say, "When this task finishes, do this next task," without manually waiting.

What is a CompletableFuture?
    Introduced in Java 8, CompletableFuture implements both the Future and CompletionStage interfaces.
    It is active and non-blocking. 
    It allows you to orchestrate complex asynchronous workflows using a functional programming style.

Feature                  Future                                                    CompletableFuture
Manual Completion        Cannot be completed manually.                             Can be manually completed using .complete(value).
                         You just wait for the task to finish.
Chaining                 No way to chain tasks together.                           "Supports chaining using .thenApply(), .thenAccept(), etc."
Non-blocking             Requires .get() (blocking) to retrieve the result.         Provides callbacks that execute automatically when the result is ready.
Exception Handling       No built-in way to handle exceptions within the pipeline.  Has dedicated methods like .exceptionally() or .handle().
Combining                You cannot easily combine multiple Future objects.         Can combine multiple stages using thenCombine() or allOf().

Why We Prefer CompletableFuture
A. Functional Chaining (The "Pipeline" approach)
    With CompletableFuture, you can define a sequence of actions that happen one after another without blocking the main thread:
        CompletableFuture.supplyAsync(() -> "Fetching Data...")
            .thenApply(data -> data + " - Processing")
            .thenAccept(finalResult -> System.out.println(finalResult));
B. Non-Blocking Orchestration
    You can trigger multiple independent tasks and act only when all of them or any of them are finished:
        allOf(): Wait for a group of independent tasks to complete.
        anyOf(): Useful when you have redundant sources and only need the fastest result.

C. Exception Handling
    In a standard Future, if something goes wrong, the exception is only thrown when you call .get(). 
    In CompletableFuture, you can catch and recover from errors gracefully:
        .exceptionally(ex -> {
            System.out.println("Error occurred: " + ex.getMessage());
            return "Default Value"; // Recover with a fallback
        })
D. Asynchronous Workflows
      It integrates perfectly with the ForkJoinPool, allowing you to perform heavy I/O or CPU-bound tasks in the background, 
      keeping your main application responsive—which is essential for modern high-performance services.

When to use which?:
    Use Future only if you are working with legacy code or have a very simple "fire and forget" task where you only need to check isDone() occasionally.
    Use CompletableFuture for everything else. It is the modern standard for writing clean, readable, and efficient asynchronous code in Java.

CompletableFuture in multiple consumer calls:
    Yes, CompletableFuture is one of the most efficient ways to handle multiple external API calls in a Java environment. 
    It is specifically designed to solve the "Aggregation" problem—where you need to fetch data from different sources and merge them into a single response.
    When dealing with external APIs, you are often waiting on I/O (network latency). 
    Instead of waiting for API A to finish before calling API B, you can fire them all at once.

How to Orchestrate Multiple API Calls:
  Depending on how your APIs depend on each other, you’ll use different patterns:

1. Parallel Execution (Independent APIs)
    If you need to call API A and API B at the same time and combine their results, use thenCombine. 
    This reduces your total response time to the duration of the slowest call, rather than the sum of both.
        CompletableFuture<User> userFuture = CompletableFuture.supplyAsync(() -> api.getUser(id));
        CompletableFuture<Order> orderFuture = CompletableFuture.supplyAsync(() -> api.getOrders(id));
        
        // Combine them when both are done
        UserOrders result = userFuture.thenCombine(orderFuture, (user, orders) -> {
            return new UserOrders(user, orders);
        }).join(); // Wait for the final merged result
2. Dependent Execution (Chaining)
    If you need the output of API A to call API B, use thenCompose. 
    This is similar to flatMap in streams; it flattens the nested futures so you don't end up with CompletableFuture<CompletableFuture<T>>.
      CompletableFuture<List<Order>> orders = CompletableFuture.supplyAsync(() -> api.getUser(id))
          .thenCompose(user -> api.getOrdersForUser(user.getAccountId()));
3. The "Fan-In" Pattern (Many APIs)
    If you are calling a variable number of APIs (e.g., fetching details for 10 different products), use CompletableFuture.allOf().
    How it works: You create a list of futures. allOf creates a new future that completes only when every single one in the list is done.
    Processing: After allOf().join(), you can map over your original list to collect the results into your final DTO.

Why This is Preferred for Microservices:
Thread Efficiency: 
      While waiting for the external API to respond, the thread is not sitting idle; 
      it's returned to the pool to handle other incoming requests.
Resilience (Timeouts): 
      You can easily attach timeouts to your external calls. 
      If API B is hanging, you can ensure it doesn't bring down your entire service:
    future.orTimeout(2, TimeUnit.SECONDS)
          .exceptionally(ex -> fallbackData);
Clean Aggregation: 
    It avoids "Callback Hell." You can keep your aggregation logic in a single service layer,
    making the code much easier to read and maintain compared to manual thread management.

What is ForkJoinPool?
  Introduced in Java 7, the ForkJoinPool is a specialized implementation of the ExecutorService designed to handle recursive tasks.
  It is built on a simple yet powerful concept: break a large, complex task into smaller sub-tasks until they are simple enough to be solved sequentially.

The framework uses two main operations:
    Fork: Recursively splitting a task into smaller independent sub-tasks.
    Join: Waiting for the sub-tasks to finish and merging their results back together.

2. The Secret Sauce: Work-Stealing Algorithm
      What makes ForkJoinPool different from a standard ThreadPoolExecutor is the Work-Stealing Algorithm.
      In a traditional thread pool, if one thread finishes its queue, it sits idle. 
      In a ForkJoinPool, every thread has its own double-ended queue (deque). 
      If a thread finishes its own work, it "steals" tasks from the back of another busy thread's queue.

Why this matters:
    This ensures maximum CPU utilization. 
    It prevents "starvation" where some threads are overworked while others are doing nothing, making it incredibly efficient for multi-core processors.

3. Where is it used?
Java Parallel Streams: When you call .parallelStream(), Java uses the Common ForkJoinPool under the hood to split the stream and process elements in parallel.
CompletableFuture: By default, if you don't provide a custom executor to supplyAsync, it runs your task in the Common ForkJoinPool.
Recursive Algorithms: It is the go-to choice for tasks like sorting large datasets (QuickSort/MergeSort), searching complex tree structures, or image processing.

4. Why We Prefer It
  A. Efficiency with Recursive Work
      Standard thread pools struggle with tasks that create more tasks. 
      If a thread in a regular pool waits for a sub-task, it stays blocked.
      In ForkJoinPool, the thread can simply pick up another sub-task while waiting, avoiding deadlocks and idle time.
  B. Optimized for Multi-core CPUs
      It is designed to scale with the hardware. 
      As modern servers move toward 16, 32, or 64-core architectures, ForkJoinPool ensures that all those cores are actually doing work rather than managing thread overhead.
  C. Low Overhead
      Managing thousands of tasks in a standard pool would create massive overhead.
     ForkJoinPool uses a small number of "worker" threads (usually equal to the number of available CPU cores) to handle a massive number of small tasks, keeping the footprint light.

When to Avoid It:
  Avoid for Blocking I/O: If your tasks spend a lot of time waiting for a database or a network API, ForkJoinPool is a poor choice.
                          Since the number of threads is limited to CPU cores, one slow API call can block an entire core. 
                          For I/O-heavy work, a standard ThreadPoolExecutor with a larger thread count is better.

  Don't Overuse the Common Pool: Since ParallelStreams and CompletableFuture share the same global pool, a single heavy task can slow down every other part of your application. 
                                In high-load microservices, it's often better to create your own dedicated ForkJoinPool for specific heavy computations.


Virtual Thread:
  A Virtual Thread is a lightweight implementation of a thread provided by the Java runtime (introduced as a stable feature in Java 21).
  Unlike traditional Platform Threads, which are wrappers around Operating System (OS) threads, virtual threads are managed entirely by the JVM.
  This allows you to run millions of threads simultaneously on a single machine without the massive memory overhead typical of OS threads.

The "Why": Solving the Throughput Problem
    In traditional Java microservices, we use a "Thread-per-Request" model.
    If your server has 200 platform threads, it can handle exactly 200 concurrent requests.
    If those requests are waiting for a database or a Kafka message, those 200 threads sit idle but still consume memory (about 1MB each).

Virtual Threads solve this by being "unmounted." 
    When a virtual thread starts a blocking I/O operation (like a SQL query), the JVM moves it off the physical thread,
    allowing that physical thread to handle a different request in the meantime.

Key Technical Concepts
1. Carrier Threads
    Virtual threads do not run on their own. 
    The JVM maintains a small pool of platform threads called Carrier Threads.
    The JVM mounts a virtual thread onto a carrier thread to execute code.
    If the code hits a blocking call, the virtual thread is unmounted.
    When the I/O finishes, the JVM remounts it (potentially on a different carrier thread) to finish the task.

2. Cheap and Lightweight
    Memory: A platform thread takes ~1MB. A virtual thread takes only a few kilobytes.
    Startup Time: Creating a virtual thread is nearly instantaneous, whereas OS threads require a syscall and memory allocation.

Feature        Platform Threads (Traditional)    Virtual Threads (Java 21)
Managed By     Operating System (OS)             Java Virtual Machine (JVM)
Creation Cost  Expensive (High CPU/RAM)          Very Cheap
Memory          ~1 MB per thread                  A few Kilobytes
Limit          Thousands (OS dependent)          Millions
Best For      CPU-intensive tasks                "I/O-bound tasks (APIs, DBs)"

In Java 21, creating a Virtual Thread is straightforward. Unlike platform threads (traditional threads), which are mapped 1:1 to OS threads, 
          virtual threads are lightweight and managed by the JVM.
You can create them using several different methods depending on your needs.

1. Using Thread.ofVirtual()
      This is the most common and readable way to start a single virtual thread. 
      You can choose to start it immediately or just create the task to be started later.
      Start immediately:
          Thread.startVirtualThread(() -> {
              System.out.println("Running in a virtual thread!");
          });
      Using the Builder (for more control):
            Thread vThread = Thread.ofVirtual()
                    .name("my-virtual-thread")
                    .unstarted(() -> {
                        System.out.println("Task logic here");
                    });
            vThread.start();
2. Using an ExecutorService
    In a microservices environment (like your Spring Boot apps), you rarely manage individual threads.
    Instead, you use an ExecutorService. Java 21 introduced a dedicated factory method for this.
    try (var executor = Executors.newVirtualThreadPerTaskExecutor()) {
        executor.submit(() -> {
            // This task runs in a new virtual thread
            System.out.println("Processing microservice request...");
        });
    } // The try-with-resources ensures the executor waits for tasks to finish
    Note: Because virtual threads are cheap, you should not pool them.
    Unlike FixedThreadPool, the newVirtualThreadPerTaskExecutor creates a brand new thread for every single task and destroys it afterward.

3. How it Works (The Concept)
    Virtual threads run on top of a pool of "Carrier Threads" (which are actual platform threads).
    When a virtual thread hits a blocking operation (like a database call or a Thread.sleep()),
    the JVM unmounts the virtual thread from the carrier thread and uses that carrier thread to run something else. Once the blocking call finishes, 
    the virtual thread is remounted and continues execution.

4. Enabling Virtual Threads in Spring Boot 3.2+
    Since you are a software engineer working with Java microservices, you likely want the framework to handle this for you.
    You can enable virtual threads globally with a single property in your application.properties:
    Properties
    spring.threads.virtual.enabled=true
    When this is set to true, Spring Boot will:
      Use virtual threads for Tomcat/Undertow web requests.
      Use virtual threads for @Async methods.
      Use virtual threads for Scheduled tasks and Message listeners (like Kafka).

Important "Dos and Don'ts":
    DO use them for I/O bound tasks (API calls, DB queries).
    DON'T pool them. Just create a new one whenever you need it.
    AVOID synchronized blocks for long-running tasks. If a virtual thread hits a synchronized block, it "pins" the carrier thread,
    preventing other virtual threads from using it. Use ReentrantLock instead.


Explain Thread pool in java Mukti threading and how to kill thread:
  It sounds like you're diving into the deep end of Java concurrency! First, a quick terminology check: you likely mean Multi-threading.
  In Java, managing threads manually is a bit like juggling chainsaws—it's efficient but dangerous. 
  That's why we use a Thread Pool.

1. What is a Thread Pool?
    Instead of creating a new thread for every single task (which is expensive and slow),
    a Thread Pool keeps a set of "worker" threads alive and ready. When a task comes in, a worker picks it up, finishes it, and then waits for the next one.
    The Core Components:
      Work Queue: Where tasks wait if all threads are busy.
      Worker Threads: The actual threads that execute the code.
      Task: The logic you want to run (usually a Runnable or Callable).

2. How to "Kill" a Thread in Java
In Java, you cannot safely force-kill a thread. 
The old Thread.stop() method was deprecated years ago because it caused data corruption and deadlocks.
Instead, Java uses an Interrupt Mechanism. You don't kill a thread; you ask it to stop nicely, and the thread must check for that request.

Option A: The Interrupt Flag
The thread should periodically check if it has been interrupted.
Thread worker = new Thread(() -> {
        while (!Thread.currentThread().isInterrupted()) {
            try {
                // Do work here
                Thread.sleep(1000); 
            } catch (InterruptedException e) {
                // When sleep is interrupted, it throws this exception
                // Clean up and exit the loop
                Thread.currentThread().interrupt(); // Preserve the status
                break; 
            }
        }
    });
    worker.start();
    // Later, to "kill" it:
    worker.interrupt();
3. How to "Kill" the Thread Pool (ExecutorService)
    If you are using an ExecutorService, you have two primary "kill" switches:
    1. shutdown() (The Gentle Approach)
      What it does: Tells the pool "No more new tasks."
      Result: It finishes tasks already in the queue but won't accept new ones. It does not stop threads that are currently running.
    2. shutdownNow() (The Aggressive Approach)
        What it does: Attempts to stop all actively executing tasks and empties the waiting queue.
        Result: It sends an interrupt() signal to every active thread.
            If your threads don't handle interrupts (as shown in the code above), they will keep running until they finish!
        The "Standard" Shutdown Pattern
        To ensure the pool is truly dead, developers usually use this three-step pattern:
        executor.shutdown(); // 1. Stop accepting new tasks
        try {
            if (!executor.awaitTermination(60, TimeUnit.SECONDS)) { // 2. Wait 60s for finish
                executor.shutdownNow(); // 3. Force interrupt if still running
            }
        } catch (InterruptedException e) {
            executor.shutdownNow();
        }
Why "Killing" is risky
  If you were to "hard kill" a thread while it’s writing to a database or a file:
  The file could get corrupted.
  The database connection might stay "locked" forever.
  Memory might not be released properly.]
The Golden Rule: Always write your thread logic to be "interruption-aware" so it can clean up its own mess before it dies.


Asynchronous vs Multi threading which is faster:
  To answer this, we first need to clarify a common misconception: Asynchronous and Multi-threading are not mutually exclusive.
  Multi-threading is a way to achieve concurrency, while Asynchronous is a design pattern for non-blocking work.
  When asking which is "faster," it depends entirely on whether your bottleneck is CPU power or Waiting (I/O).

1. Multi-threading (The Worker Approach)
    Multi-threading is like hiring 5 chefs to cook 5 different meals.
    How it works: The OS gives each thread a slice of CPU time. In a multi-core system, threads actually run in parallel.
    The Cost: Threads are "heavy." Each thread consumes memory (stack size) and takes time for the CPU to switch between them (Context Switching).
    Best for: CPU-intensive tasks (e.g., video encoding, heavy mathematical calculations, data processing).

2. Asynchronous (The Single-Chef Approach)
    Asynchronous programming is like one chef who starts the pasta, sets a timer, and then immediately starts chopping vegetables while the water boils. 
    They don't stand still staring at the pot.
    How it works: Usually runs on a single thread (or a very small pool). It uses an Event Loop. 
          When a task is waiting for something (like a database response or a file read), the thread moves to the next task instead of idling.
    The Cost: Very low memory overhead. You can handle thousands of concurrent connections with just one thread.
    Best for: I/O-intensive tasks (e.g., Web servers, API calls, reading/writing files).

3. Performance Comparison
Feature               Multi-threading                        Asynchronous
Speed (Small Tasks)  "Fast, but hits a limit quickly."       Extremely fast for high-volume I/O.
Resource Usage        High (Memory per thread).              Low (Uses very few threads).
Complexity            "High (Deadlocks, Race conditions)."  "High (Callback hell, Promise chaining)."
Ideal Use Case        "Complex math, Image processing."      "Web Servers, Chat Apps, Scrapers."

Which is "Faster"?
  If you are calculating Pi to a billion digits: Multi-threading is faster. 
  You need the raw power of multiple CPU cores working simultaneously.
  
  If you are handling 10,000 users requesting a webpage: Asynchronous is faster. 
  If you tried to create 10,000 threads, your server would likely crash from memory exhaustion (RAM) and spend all its time switching between threads rather than doing work.

The Modern Hybrid
  In the real world (especially in Java with CompletableFuture or Virtual Threads in Java 21), we often use both.
  We use Asynchronous code to keep the application responsive while waiting for I/O, and we use a Thread Pool to handle the heavy lifting in the background.

Blocking Queue:
  The Blocking Queue is actually the bridge that connects these two concepts. 
  If you had to pick which one it is most similar to in terms of behavior, it is the fundamental heart of Multi-threading.
  
  Think of it this way: Multi-threading is the "engine," Asynchronous is the "driving style,"
  and the Blocking Queue is the "transmission" that connects the engine to the wheels.

1. Why it is similar to Multi-threading
  The Blocking Queue is a synchronization primitive. Its entire purpose is to manage multiple threads safely.
  Thread Safety: It uses internal locks (like ReentrantLock) to ensure that if two threads try to grab the same item at the exact same microsecond, only one gets it.
  Wait/Notify: It handles the complex logic of putting a thread to sleep and waking it up—the core of multi-threaded coordination.

2. Is it similar to Asynchronous?
  In terms of "Vibe": Yes. In terms of "Mechanism": No.
  The Similarity: Both allow a "Fire and Forget" approach. 
    You (the Producer) can drop a task into the queue and walk away to do other things. This feels asynchronous.
  The Difference: A Blocking Queue is Blocking (the name is the giveaway!). 
    If the queue is full, the thread stops and waits. In a truly Asynchronous (non-blocking) system, the thread would never stop; it would receive a notification or "Promise" when space becomes available.

3. The Comparison Table
Feature    Blocking Queue                        Multi-threading                      Asynchronous
Role      The Storage & Coordinator.             The Workers (Execution).            The Pattern (Strategy).
Blocking?  Yes. Threads wait if empty/full.      Yes. Threads wait for CPU slices.    No. Threads move to other tasks.
Analogy    "A restaurant's ""Order Heat Lamp.""  The Chefs in the kitchen.            The Waiter taking many orders.

4. How they all work together in Java
    If you look at a standard Java ThreadPoolExecutor, you will see all three concepts working at once:
    Multi-threading: The pool creates 10 worker threads.
    Blocking Queue: The pool uses a LinkedBlockingQueue to hold tasks.
    Asynchronous: When you call executor.submit(), it returns a Future (asynchronous handle). 
      Your main thread keeps running while the worker threads grab tasks from the Blocking Queue.

The Verdict
The Blocking Queue is a Multi-threading tool used to create Asynchronous behavior.
Without a Blocking Queue, you couldn't have an efficient Thread Pool, and without a Thread Pool, 
  most of your favorite Asynchronous libraries (like CompletableFuture) wouldn't have any threads to run on!

What will happen if thread are full:  
  When you reach the point where all threads in your pool are busy and the "waiting room" (the Queue) is also packed,
  the system hits a critical limit. In Java's ThreadPoolExecutor, this is handled by a RejectedExecutionHandler.

Here is exactly what happens, step-by-step:
1. The Workflow of a Full Pool
    To understand what happens when it's full, you have to look at the "Order of Operations":
    Core Threads: The pool tries to give the task to an idle core thread.
    The Queue: If core threads are busy, the task is placed in the Blocking Queue.
    Maximum Threads: If the queue is full, the pool creates new threads up to the maximumPoolSize.
    Rejection: If the queue is full AND the max threads are all busy, the task is Rejected.

2. The 4 Default Rejection Policies
    Java provides four standard ways to handle a "full" situation. 
    You can choose which one fits your app's needs: 
    Policy                      What happens to the task?                                Impact
    AbortPolicy (Default)      Throws a RejectedExecutionException.                     The program crashes or must catch the error.
    CallerRunsPolicy           The thread that submitted the task executes it itself.    Slows down the whole system (throttles the producer).
    DiscardPolicy              The task is silently dropped.                            "Data is lost, but the system stays stable."
    DiscardOldestPolicy        The oldest task in the queue is deleted to make room.     Focuses on the most recent data.

3. The "System Impact" (Why it's dangerous)
When threads are full, your application begins to exhibit several symptoms:
    Increased Latency: If tasks are sitting in a long queue, the "response time" for a user increases significantly.
    Memory Pressure: If your queue is "Unbounded" (can grow forever), it will eventually consume all your RAM, leading to an OutOfMemoryError (OOM).
    CPU Spikes: If the pool is constantly trying to create and destroy threads to keep up, the CPU spends more time managing threads than doing actual work.
    Cascading Failure: If Service A is full, Service B (which calls Service A) also starts backing up. This is how entire systems crash.

4. How to prevent "Full Thread" issues
To keep your system healthy, you should follow these patterns:
    Use Bounded Queues: Never use a queue that can grow infinitely. Set a limit (e.g., 1,000 tasks).
    Apply Backpressure: Use the CallerRunsPolicy. It forces the "sender" to do the work, which naturally slows down the incoming request rate.
    Monitoring: Use tools to watch the getPoolSize() and getQueue().size() metrics so you can scale your hardware before it hits the limit.
    Virtual Threads (Java 21+): If your threads are full because they are waiting on I/O (Database/API), 
        switching to Virtual Threads allows you to have millions of threads without the memory overhead of traditional threads.

What happen in parallel processing in executor service for one flow exception occurs , will it stop or continue?

In an ExecutorService,The pool itself continues to live, but that specific thread might die (and be replaced), and the specific task fails.
An exception in one flow does not automatically kill the entire Thread Pool or stop other threads from working.
However, how you "see" that exception depends entirely on how you submitted the task.

1. The "Silent Failure" (execute)
    If you use executor.execute(Runnable task), the exception is handled by the thread's uncaught exception handler.
    The Result: The exception is printed to System.err, the thread is terminated, 
          and the ExecutorService creates a new thread to replace it to keep the pool size consistent.
    Other Tasks: All other tasks currently running or waiting in the queue continue as if nothing happened.

2. The "Hidden Failure" (submit)
    If you use executor.submit(Callable/Runnable task), the exception is captured and stored inside a Future object.
    The Result: No exception is printed to the console immediately.
            The thread stays alive and moves on to the next task in the queue.
    How to see it: You only discover the exception when you call future.get().
            At that point, it will throw an ExecutionException.

    Future<?> future = executor.submit(() -> {
        throw new RuntimeException("Boom!");
    });
    
    try {
        future.get(); // The exception is thrown HERE
    } catch (ExecutionException e) {
        System.out.println("Caught the task failure: " + e.getCause());
    }
3. What if you want EVERYTHING to stop?
    By default, the ExecutorService is designed for isolation—one task's failure shouldn't ruin everyone else's day.
    But if you want the whole flow to stop when one task fails, you have to manage it manually:

      The "InvokeAny" Pattern
      If you use executor.invokeAny(tasks), it returns the result of the first successful task. If all tasks fail, it throws an exception.
      The Manual "Kill Switch"
      If you have 10 tasks and want to cancel them all if one fails, you can catch the exception and call shutdownNow():
      
          try {
              // some logic
          } catch (Exception e) {
              // If one fails, kill the whole pool immediately
              executor.shutdownNow(); 
          }
4. Special Case: ScheduledExecutorService
    Be very careful with ScheduledExecutorService. If a task running at a fixed rate (e.g., every 5 seconds) throws an exception:
    The task stops forever. * The scheduler will not run that task again.
    It doesn't kill the pool, but it kills that specific recurring schedule. You must wrap your scheduled logic in a try-catch to keep it running.

Summary
  Does the Pool stop? No.
  Does the Task stop? Yes, immediately.
  Do other threads stop? No, they are isolated.
  Does the thread die? Usually, it is returned to the pool (if using submit) or replaced (if using execute).
